<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="46" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="47.[192,1440,195,284]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,346,195,219]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named in honor of Armando Luis-Martínez of 
<collectingRegion box="[1074,1218,195,219]" country="Mexico" name="Distrito Federal" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Mexico City</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1229,1318,195,219]" name="Mexico" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Armando has been a leading researcher in efforts to document Mexico’s butterfly diversity for over two decades, and has been a friend and close colleague of the junior author for 15 years.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="46" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="47.[192,1440,323,443]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,585,323,347]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Distribution and phenology.</emphasis>
To date, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[700,858,323,347]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armandoi">
<emphasis box="[700,858,323,347]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. armandoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the vicinity of 
<collectingRegion box="[1286,1395,323,347]" country="Costa Rica" name="San Jose" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">San Jose</collectingRegion>
del Pacifico, in the Municipality of San Mateo Río Hondo, in the Sierra Madre del Sur of 
<collectingRegion box="[1200,1294,355,379]" country="Mexico" name="Oaxaca" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Oaxaca</collectingRegion>
, along Hwy. 175, between 2280 and 
<quantity box="[480,573,387,411]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.4" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" unit="m" value="2400.0">2400 m</quantity>
. Both known specimens were collected during the local rainy season of September, 2007 and October, 2008.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="47.[192,1440,483,603]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,423,483,507]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Biological notes.</emphasis>
The male 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[555,714,483,507]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armandoi">
<emphasis box="[555,714,483,507]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. armandoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
taken by the junior author was perching in a small sunny opening, at the junction of two trails along a creek in montane coniferous forest, about one meter above ground level, at about 10:00 h. Various grasses are common in this habitat, although no 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kunth" authorityYear="1822" box="[1263,1386,547,571]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Chusquea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1263,1386,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Chusquea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was observed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="47" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="47.[192,1440,643,827]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,548,643,667]" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis and discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[554,772,643,667]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armandoi">
<emphasis box="[554,772,643,667]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">Neposa armandoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is nearly the size of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1018,1121,643,667]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis box="[1018,1121,643,667]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but appears more orange since the entire postmedial series of macules on the forewing is well-developed. Similarly, the ventral forewing has broader expanses of orange at the expense of black compared to that wing of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1265,1366,707,731]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis box="[1265,1366,707,731]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Male genitalia of the two species, although having a similar gestalt, exhibit several differences. On 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[1281,1433,739,763]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armandoi">
<emphasis box="[1281,1433,739,763]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. armandoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the gnathos is nearly the length of the uncus whereas it is longer than the uncus on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[1204,1306,771,795]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis box="[1204,1306,771,795]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The valva of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin and A. Warren" authorityYear="2009" box="[220,378,803,827]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="armandoi">
<emphasis box="[220,378,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. armandoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is conspicuously longer and broader than on 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Austin &amp; Warren" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Godman" baseAuthorityYear="1900" box="[927,1031,803,827]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Neposa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="47" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="heras">
<emphasis box="[927,1031,803,827]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="46">N. heras</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and is curved (vs. angled).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
